# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: phase-diagrams
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:phase-diagrams/binary-phase] In materials chemistry, a **binary phase** or **binary compound** is a chemical compound containing two different elements.
[src:phase-diagrams/binary-phase] Some binary phase compounds are molecular, e.g. carbon tetrachloride (CCl4).
[src:phase-diagrams/binary-phase] More typically binary phase refers to extended solids.
[src:phase-diagrams/binary-phase] Famous examples zinc sulfide, which contains zinc and sulfur, and tungsten carbide, which contains tungsten and carbon.
[src:phase-diagrams/binary-phase] Phases with higher degrees of complexity feature more elements, e.g. three elements in ternary phases, four elements in quaternary phases.
[src:phase-diagrams/binary-phase] These phases exhibit a higher degree of complexity due to the interaction of these elements at different conditions.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] A **eutectic system** or **eutectic mixture** (/juːˈtɛktɪk/ *yoo-TEK-tik*) is a type of a homogeneous mixture that has a melting point lower than those of the constituents.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] The lowest possible melting point over all of the mixing ratios of the constituents is called the *eutectic temperature*.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] On a phase diagram, the eutectic temperature is seen as the eutectic point (see plot).
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Non-eutectic mixture ratios have different melting temperatures for their different constituents, since one component's lattice will melt at a lower temperature than the other's.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Conversely, as a non-eutectic mixture cools down, each of its components solidifies into a lattice at a different temperature, until the entire mass is solid.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] A non-eutectic mixture thus does not have a single melting/freezing point temperature at which it changes phase, but rather a temperature at which it changes between liquid and slush (known as the liquidus) and a lower temperature at which it changes between slush and solid (the solidus).
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] The term *eutectic* was coined in 1884 by the British physicist and chemist Frederick Guthrie (1833–1886).
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] The word originates from Greek εὐ*- (eû)* 'well' and τῆξῐς*(têxis)* 'melting'.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Before his studies, chemists assumed "that the alloy of minimum fusing point must have its constituents in some simple atomic proportions", but he showed that that is not always true.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] This type of reaction is an invariant reaction, because it is in thermal equilibrium; another way to define this is the change in Gibbs free energy equals zero.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Tangibly, this means the liquid and two solid solutions all coexist at the same time and are in chemical equilibrium.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] There is also a thermal arrest for the duration of the phase change during which the temperature of the system does not change.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] The resulting solid macrostructure from a eutectic reaction depends on a few factors, with the most important factor being how the two solid solutions nucleate and grow.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] The most common structure is a lamellar structure, but other possible structures include rodlike, globular, and acicular.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Besides, a vermicular microstructure has been observed in a high-entropy alloy.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] As the temperature of a non-eutectic composition is lowered the liquid mixture will precipitate one component of the mixture before the other.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] In a hypereutectic solution, there will be a *proeutectoid* phase of species β whereas a hypoeutectic solution will have a *proeutectic* α phase.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Eutectic alloys have two or more materials and have a eutectic composition.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] When a non-eutectic alloy solidifies, its components solidify at different temperatures, exhibiting a plastic melting range.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Conversely, when a well-mixed, eutectic alloy melts, it does so at a single, sharp temperature.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] The various phase transformations that occur during the solidification of a particular alloy composition can be understood by drawing a vertical line from the liquid phase to the solid phase on the phase diagram for that alloy.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] The primary strengthening mechanism of the eutectic structure in metals is composite strengthening (See strengthening mechanisms of materials).
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] This deformation mechanism works through load transfer between the two constituent phases where the more compliant phase transfers stress to the stiffer phase.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] By taking advantage of the strength of the stiff phase and the ductility of the compliant phase, the overall toughness of the material increases.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] As the composition is varied to either hypoeutectic or hypereutectic formations, the load transfer mechanism becomes more complex as there is a load transfer between the eutectic phase and the secondary phase as well as the load transfer within the eutectic phase itself.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] A second tunable strengthening mechanism of eutectic structures is the spacing of the secondary phase.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] By changing the spacing of the secondary phase, the fraction of contact between the two phases through shared phase boundaries is also changed.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] By decreasing the spacing of the eutectic phase, creating a fine eutectic structure, more surface area is shared between the two constituent phases resulting in more effective load transfer.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] On the micro-scale, the additional boundary area acts as a barrier to dislocations further strengthening the material.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] As a result of this strengthening mechanism, coarse eutectic structures tend to be less stiff but more ductile while fine eutectic structures are stiffer but more brittle.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] The spacing of the eutectic phase can be controlled during processing as it is directly related to the cooling rate during solidification of the eutectic structure.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] So, by altering the undercooling, and by extension the cooling rate, the minimal achievable spacing of the secondary phase is controlled.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Strengthening metallic eutectic phases to resist deformation at high temperatures (see creep deformation) is more convoluted as the primary deformation mechanism changes depending on the level of stress applied.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] At high temperatures where deformation is dominated by dislocation movement, the strengthening from load transfer and secondary phase spacing remain as they continue to resist dislocation motion.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] At lower strains where Nabarro-Herring creep is dominant, the shape and size of the eutectic phase structure plays a significant role in material deformation as it affects the available boundary area for vacancy diffusion to occur.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] When the solution above the transformation point is solid, rather than liquid, an analogous eutectoid transformation can occur.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] For instance, in the iron-carbon system, the austenite phase can undergo a eutectoid transformation to produce ferrite and cementite, often in lamellar structures such as pearlite and bainite.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] This eutectoid point occurs at 723 °C (1,333 °F) and 0.76 wt% carbon.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] A *peritectoid* transformation is a type of isothermal reversible reaction that has two solid phases reacting with each other upon cooling of a binary, ternary, ..., *n*-ary alloy to create a completely different and single solid phase.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] The reaction plays a key role in the order and decomposition of quasicrystalline phases in several alloy types.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] A similar structural transition is also predicted for rotating columnar crystals.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Peritectic transformations are also similar to eutectic reactions.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Here, a liquid and solid phase of fixed proportions react at a fixed temperature to yield a single solid phase.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Since the solid product forms at the interface between the two reactants, it can form a diffusion barrier and generally causes such reactions to proceed much more slowly than eutectic or eutectoid transformations.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Because of this, when a peritectic composition solidifies it does not show the lamellar structure that is found with eutectic solidification.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Such a transformation exists in the iron-carbon system, as seen near the upper-left corner of the figure.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] It resembles an inverted eutectic, with the δ phase combining with the liquid to produce pure austenite at 1,495 °C (2,723 °F) and 0.17% carbon.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] At the peritectic decomposition temperature the compound, rather than melting, decomposes into another solid compound and a liquid.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] The proportion of each is determined by the lever rule.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] In the Al-Au phase diagram, for example, it can be seen that only two of the phases melt congruently, AuAl2 and Au2Al, while the rest peritectically decompose.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Not all minimum melting point systems are "eutectic".
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] The alternative of "poor solid solution" can be illustrated by comparing the common precious metal systems Cu-Ag and Cu-Au.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Cu-Ag, source for example https://himikatus.ru/art/phase-diagr1/Ag-Cu.php, is a true eutectic system.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] The eutectic melting point is at 780 °C, with solid solubility limits at fineness 80 and 912 by weight, and eutectic at 719.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Since Cu-Ag is a true eutectic, any silver with fineness anywhere between 80 and 912 will reach solidus line, and therefore melt at least partly, at exactly 780 °C.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] The eutectic alloy with fineness exactly 719 will reach liquidus line, and therefore melt entirely, at that exact temperature without any further rise of temperature till all of the alloy has melted.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Any silver with fineness between 80 and 912 but not exactly 719 will also reach the solidus line at exactly 780 °C, but will melt partly.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] It will leave a solid residue with fineness of either exactly 912 or exactly 80, but never some of both.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] It will melt at constant temperature without further rise of temperature until the exact amount of eutectic (fineness 719) alloy has melted off to divide the alloy into eutectic melt and solid solution residue.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] On further heating, the solid solution residue dissolves in the melt and changes its composition until the liquidus line is reached and the whole residue has dissolved away.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Cu-Au source for example https://himikatus.ru/art/phase-diagr1/Au-Cu.php does display a melting point minimum at 910 °C and given as 44 atom % Cu, which converts to about 20 weight percent Cu - about 800 fineness of gold.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] 800 fine gold melts at 910 °C, to a melt of the same composition, and the whole alloy will melt at the same temperature.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] But the differences happen away from the minimum composition.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Unlike silver with fineness other than 719 (which melts partly at exactly 780 °C through a wide fineness range), gold with fineness other than 800 will reach solidus and start partial melting at a temperature different from and higher than 910 °C, depending on the alloy fineness.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] The partial melting does cause some composition changes - the liquid will be closer in fineness towards 800 than the remaining solid, but the liquid will not have fineness of exactly 800 and the fineness of the remaining solid will depend on the fineness of the liquid.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] The underlying reason is that for an eutectic system like Cu-Ag, the solubility in liquid phase is good but solubility in solid phase is limited.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Therefore when a silver-copper alloy is frozen, it actually separates into crystals of 912 fineness silver and 80 fineness silver - both are saturated and always have the same composition at the freezing point of 780 °C.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Thus the alloy just below 780 °C consists of two types of crystals of exactly the same composition regardless of the total alloy composition, only the relative amount of each type of crystals differs.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] Therefore they always melt at 780 °C until one or other type of crystals, or both, will be exhausted.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] In contrast, in Cu-Au system the components are miscible at the melting point in all compositions even in solid.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] There can be crystals of any composition, which will melt at different temperatures depending on composition.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] However, Cu-Au system is a "poor" solid solution.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] There is a substantial misfit between the atoms in solid which, however, near the melting point is overcome by entropy of thermal motion mixing the atoms.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] That misfit, however, disfavours the Cu-Au solution relative to phases in which the atoms are better fitted, such as the melt, and causes the melting point to fall below the melting point of components.
[src:phase-diagrams/eutectic-system] The composition and temperature of a eutectic can be calculated from enthalpy and entropy of fusion of each components.
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] In chemistry, the **lever rule** is a formula used to determine the mole fraction (*xi*) or the mass fraction (*wi*) of each phase of a binary equilibrium phase diagram.
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] It can be used to determine the fraction of liquid and solid phases for a given binary composition and temperature that is between the liquidus and solidus line.
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] all at some fixed temperature or pressure.
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] Suppose an alloy at an equilibrium temperature *T* consists of $w_{\rm {B}}$ mass fraction of element B.
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] Suppose also that at temperature *T* the alloy consists of two phases, α and β, for which the α consists of $w_{\rm {B}}^{\alpha }$ , and β consists of $w_{\rm {B}}^{\beta }$ .
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] Let the mass of the α phase in the alloy be $m^{\alpha }$ so that the mass of the β phase is $m^{\beta }=m-m^{\alpha }$ , where m is the total mass of the alloy.
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] By definition, then, the mass of element B in the α phase is $m_{\rm {B}}^{\alpha }=w_{\rm {B}}^{\alpha }m^{\alpha }$ , while the mass of element B in the β phase is $m_{\rm {B}}^{\beta }=w_{\rm {B}}^{\beta }\left(m-m^{\alpha }\right)$ .
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] Together these two quantities sum to the total mass of element B in the alloy, which is given by $m_{\rm {B}}=w_{\rm {B}}m$ .
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] This final fraction is the mass fraction of the α phase in the alloy.
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] Before any calculations can be made, a *tie line* is drawn on the phase diagram to determine the mass fraction of each element; on the phase diagram to the right it is line segment LS.
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] This tie line is drawn horizontally at the composition's temperature from one phase to another (here the liquid to the solid).
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] The mass fraction of element B at the liquidus is given by *w*Bl (represented as *w*l in this diagram) and the mass fraction of element B at the solidus is given by *w*Bs (represented as *w*s in this diagram).
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] where *w*B is the mass fraction of element B for the given composition (represented as *w*o in this diagram).
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] The numerator of each equation is the original composition that we are interested in is +/- the **opposite** *lever arm*.
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] That is if you want the mass fraction of solid then take the difference between the liquid composition and the original composition.
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] And then the denominator is the overall length of the arm so the difference between the solid and liquid compositions.
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] If you're having difficulty realising why this is so, try visualising the composition when *w*o approaches *w*l.
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] Then the liquid concentration will start increasing.
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] There is now more than one two-phase region.
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] The tie line drawn is from the solid alpha to the liquid and by dropping a vertical line down at these points the mass fraction of each phase is directly read off the graph, that is the mass fraction in the x axis element.
[src:phase-diagrams/lever-rule] The same equations can be used to find the mass fraction of alloy in each of the phases, i.e. wl is the mass fraction of the whole sample in the liquid phase.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] A **phase diagram** in physical chemistry, engineering, mineralogy, and materials science is a type of chart used to show conditions (pressure, temperature, etc.) at which thermodynamically distinct phases (such as solid, liquid or gaseous states) occur and coexist at equilibrium.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Common components of a phase diagram are *lines of equilibrium* or *phase boundaries*, which refer to lines that mark conditions under which multiple phases can coexist at equilibrium.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Phase transitions occur along lines of equilibrium.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Metastable phases are not shown in phase diagrams as, despite their common occurrence, they are not equilibrium phases.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Triple points are points on phase diagrams where lines of equilibrium intersect.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Triple points mark conditions at which three different phases can coexist.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] For example, the water phase diagram has a triple point corresponding to the single temperature and pressure at which solid, liquid, and gaseous water can coexist in a stable equilibrium (273.16 K and a partial vapor pressure of 611.657 Pa).
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The pressure on a pressure-temperature diagram (such as the water phase diagram shown) is that of the substance in question (e.g., the environmental pressure for a condensed state and the partial pressure for the gas state).
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The solidus is the temperature below which the substance is stable in the solid state.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The liquidus is the temperature above which the substance is stable in a liquid state.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] There may be a gap between the solidus and liquidus; within the gap, the substance consists of a mixture of crystals and liquid (like a "slurry").
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Working fluids are often categorized on the basis of the shape of their phase diagram.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The simplest phase diagrams are pressure–temperature diagrams of a single simple substance, such as water.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The axes correspond to the pressure and temperature.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The phase diagram shows, in pressure–temperature space, the lines of equilibrium or phase boundaries between the three phases of solid, liquid, and gas.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The curves on the phase diagram show the points where the free energy (and other derived properties) becomes non-analytic: their derivatives with respect to the coordinates (temperature and pressure in this example) change discontinuously (abruptly).
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] For example, the heat capacity of a container filled with ice will change abruptly as the container is heated past the melting point.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The open spaces, where the free energy is analytic, correspond to single phase regions.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Single phase regions are separated by lines of non-analytical behavior, where phase transitions occur, which are called **phase boundaries**.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] In the diagram on the right, the phase boundary between liquid and gas does not continue indefinitely.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Instead, it terminates at a point on the phase diagram called the critical point.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] This reflects the fact that, at extremely high temperatures and pressures, the liquid and gaseous phases become indistinguishable, in what is known as a supercritical fluid.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The existence of the liquid–gas critical point reveals a slight ambiguity in labelling the single phase regions.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] When going from the liquid to the gaseous phase, one usually crosses the phase boundary, but it is possible to choose a path that never crosses the boundary by going to the right of the critical point.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Thus, the liquid and gaseous phases can blend continuously into each other.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The solid–liquid phase boundary can only end in a critical point if the solid and liquid phases have the same symmetry group.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] For most substances, the solid–liquid phase boundary (or fusion curve) in the phase diagram has a positive slope so that the melting point increases with pressure.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] This is true whenever the solid phase is denser than the liquid phase.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The greater the pressure on a given substance, the closer together the molecules of the substance are brought to each other, which increases the effect of the substance's intermolecular forces.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Thus, the substance requires a higher temperature for its molecules to have enough energy to break out of the fixed pattern of the solid phase and enter the liquid phase.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] A similar concept applies to liquid–gas phase changes.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Water is an exception which has a solid-liquid boundary with negative slope so that the melting point decreases with pressure.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] This occurs because ice (solid water) is less dense than liquid water, as shown by the fact that ice floats on water.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] At a molecular level, ice is less dense because it has a more extensive network of hydrogen bonding which requires a greater separation of water molecules.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Other exceptions include antimony and bismuth.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] At very high pressures above 50 GPa (500 000 atm), liquid nitrogen undergoes a liquid-liquid phase transition to a polymeric form and becomes denser than solid nitrogen at the same pressure.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Under these conditions therefore, solid nitrogen also floats in its liquid.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] where Δ*H*fus is the heat of fusion which is always positive, and Δ*V*fus is the volume change for fusion.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] For most substances Δ*V*fus is positive so that the slope is positive.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] However for water and other exceptions, Δ*V*fus is negative so that the slope is negative.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] In addition to temperature and pressure, other thermodynamic properties may be graphed in phase diagrams.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Examples of such thermodynamic properties include specific volume, specific enthalpy, or specific entropy.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] For example, single-component graphs of temperature vs. specific entropy (*T* vs.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] *s*) for water/steam or for a refrigerant are commonly used to illustrate thermodynamic cycles such as a Carnot cycle, Rankine cycle, or vapor-compression refrigeration cycle.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Any two thermodynamic quantities may be shown on the horizontal and vertical axes of a two-dimensional diagram.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Additional thermodynamic quantities may each be illustrated in increments as a series of lines—curved, straight, or a combination of curved and straight.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Each of these **iso-**lines represents the thermodynamic quantity at a certain constant value.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] It is possible to envision three-dimensional (3D) graphs showing three thermodynamic quantities.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] For example, for a single component, a 3D Cartesian coordinate type graph can show temperature (*T*) on one axis, pressure (*p*) on a second axis, and specific volume (*v*) on a third.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Such a 3D graph is sometimes called a *p*–*v*–*T* diagram.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The equilibrium conditions are shown as curves on a curved surface in 3D with areas for solid, liquid, and vapor phases and areas where solid and liquid, solid and vapor, or liquid and vapor coexist in equilibrium.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] A line on the surface called a **triple line** is where solid, liquid and vapor can all coexist in equilibrium.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The critical point remains a point on the surface even on a 3D phase diagram.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] An orthographic projection of the 3D *p*–*v*–*T* graph showing pressure and temperature as the vertical and horizontal axes collapses the 3D plot into the standard 2D pressure–temperature diagram.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] When this is done, the solid–vapor, solid–liquid, and liquid–vapor surfaces collapse into three corresponding curved lines meeting at the triple point, which is the collapsed orthographic projection of the triple line.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Other much more complex types of phase diagrams can be constructed, particularly when more than one pure component is present.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] In that case, concentration becomes an important variable.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Phase diagrams with more than two dimensions can be constructed that show the effect of more than two variables on the phase of a substance.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Phase diagrams can use other variables in addition to or in place of temperature, pressure and composition, for example the strength of an applied electrical or magnetic field, and they can also involve substances that take on more than just three states of matter.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] One type of phase diagram plots temperature against the relative concentrations of two substances in a binary mixture called a *binary phase diagram*, as shown at right.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Such a mixture can be either a solid solution, eutectic or peritectic, among others.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] These two types of mixtures result in very different graphs.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Another type of binary phase diagram is a *boiling-point diagram* for a mixture of two components, i. e. chemical compounds.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] For two particular volatile components at a certain pressure such as atmospheric pressure, a boiling-point diagram shows what vapor (gas) compositions are in equilibrium with given liquid compositions depending on temperature.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] In a typical binary boiling-point diagram, temperature is plotted on a vertical axis and mixture composition on a horizontal axis.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] A two component diagram with components A and B in an "ideal" solution is shown.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The construction of a liquid vapor phase diagram assumes an ideal liquid solution obeying Raoult's law and an ideal gas mixture obeying Dalton's law of partial pressure.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] A tie line from the liquid to the gas at constant pressure would indicate the two compositions of the liquid and gas respectively.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] A simple example diagram with hypothetical components 1 and 2 in a non-azeotropic mixture is shown at right.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The fact that there are two separate curved lines joining the boiling points of the pure components means that the vapor composition is usually not the same as the liquid composition the vapor is in equilibrium with.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] See Vapor–liquid equilibrium for more information.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] In addition to the above-mentioned types of phase diagrams, there are many other possible combinations.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Some of the major features of phase diagrams include congruent points, where a solid phase transforms directly into a liquid.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] There is also the peritectoid, a point where two solid phases combine into one solid phase during cooling.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The inverse of this, when one solid phase transforms into two solid phases during cooling, is called the eutectoid.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] A complex phase diagram of great technological importance is that of the iron–carbon system for less than 7% carbon (see steel).
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The x-axis of such a diagram represents the concentration variable of the mixture.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] As the mixtures are typically far from dilute and their density as a function of temperature is usually unknown, the preferred concentration measure is mole fraction.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] A volume-based measure like molarity would be inadvisable.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] A system with three components is called a ternary system.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] At constant pressure the maximum number of independent variables is three – the temperature and two concentration values.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] For a representation of ternary equilibria a three-dimensional phase diagram is required.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Often such a diagram is drawn with the composition as a horizontal plane and the temperature on an axis perpendicular to this plane.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] To represent composition in a ternary system an equilateral triangle is used, called Gibbs triangle (see also Ternary plot).
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The temperature scale is plotted on the axis perpendicular to the composition triangle.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Thus, the space model of a ternary phase diagram is a right-triangular prism.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] The prism sides represent corresponding binary systems A-B, B-C, A-C.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] However, the most common methods to present phase equilibria in a ternary system are the following: 1) projections on the concentration triangle ABC of the liquidus, solidus, solvus surfaces; 2) isothermal sections; 3) vertical sections.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Polymorphic and polyamorphic substances have multiple crystal or amorphous phases, which can be graphed in a similar fashion to solid, liquid, and gas phases.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Some organic materials pass through intermediate states between solid and liquid; these states are called mesophases.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Attention has been directed to mesophases because they enable display devices and have become commercially important through the so-called liquid-crystal technology.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-diagram] Phase diagrams are used to describe the occurrence of mesophases.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] In thermodynamics, the **phase rule** is a general principle governing multi-component, multi-phase systems in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] Examples of intensive properties that count toward F are the temperature and pressure.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] For simple liquids and gases, pressure-volume work is the only type of work, in which case *N* = 1.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] The rule was derived by American physicist Josiah Willard Gibbs in his landmark paper titled *On the Equilibrium of Heterogeneous Substances*, published in parts between 1875 and 1878.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] The number of degrees of freedom F (also called the *variance*) is the number of independent intensive properties, *i.e.*, the largest number of thermodynamic parameters such as temperature or pressure that can be varied simultaneously and independently of each other.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] An example of a one-component system (*C* = 1) is a pure chemical.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] A two-component system (*C* = 2) has two chemically independent components, like a mixture of water and ethanol.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] Examples of phases that count toward P are solids, liquids and gases.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] The basis for the rule is that equilibrium between phases places a constraint on the intensive variables.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] More rigorously, since the phases are in thermodynamic equilibrium with each other, the chemical potentials of the phases must be equal.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] The number of equality relationships determines the number of degrees of freedom.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] For example, if the chemical potentials of a liquid and of its vapour depend on temperature (*T*) and pressure (*p*), the equality of chemical potentials will mean that each of those variables will be dependent on the other.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] Mathematically, the equation *μ*liq(*T*, *p*) = *μ*vap(*T*, *p*), where *μ*, the chemical potential, defines temperature as a function of pressure or vice versa.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] To be more specific, the composition of each phase is determined by *C* − *1* intensive variables (such as mole fractions) in each phase.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] The total number of variables is (*C* − 1)*P* + 2, where the extra two are temperature *T* and pressure *p*.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] The number of constraints is *C*(*P* − 1), since the chemical potential of each component must be equal in all phases.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] Subtract the number of constraints from the number of variables to obtain the number of degrees of freedom as *F* = (*C* − 1)*P* + 2 − *C*(*P* − 1) = *C* − *P* + 2.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] The rule is valid provided the equilibrium between phases is not influenced by gravitational, electrical or magnetic forces, or by surface area, and only by temperature, pressure, and concentration.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] For pure substances *C* = 1 so that *F* = 3 − *P*.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] In a single phase (*P* = 1) condition of a pure component system, two variables (*F* = 2), such as temperature and pressure, can be chosen independently to be any pair of values consistent with the phase.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] However, if the temperature and pressure combination ranges to a point where the pure component undergoes a separation into two phases (*P* = 2), *F* decreases from 2 to 1.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] When the system enters the two-phase region, it is no longer possible to independently control temperature and pressure.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] In the phase diagram to the right, the boundary curve between the liquid and gas regions maps the constraint between temperature and pressure when the single-component system has separated into liquid and gas phases at equilibrium.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] The only way to increase the pressure on the two phase line is by increasing the temperature.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] If the temperature is decreased by cooling, some of the gas condenses, decreasing the pressure.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] Throughout both processes, the temperature and pressure stay in the relationship shown by this boundary curve unless one phase is entirely consumed by evaporation or condensation, or unless the critical point is reached.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] As long as there are two phases, there is only one degree of freedom, which corresponds to the position along the phase boundary curve.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] The critical point is the black dot at the end of the liquid–gas boundary.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] As this point is approached, the liquid and gas phases become progressively more similar until, at the critical point, there is no longer a separation into two phases.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] Above the critical point and away from the phase boundary curve, *F* = 2 and the temperature and pressure can be controlled independently.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] Hence there is only one phase, and it has the physical properties of a dense gas, but is also referred to as a supercritical fluid.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] Of the other two-boundary curves, one is the solid–liquid boundary or melting point curve which indicates the conditions for equilibrium between these two phases, and the other at lower temperature and pressure is the solid–gas boundary.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] Even for a pure substance, it is possible that three phases, such as solid, liquid and vapour, can exist together in equilibrium (*P* = 3).
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] If there is only one component, there are no degrees of freedom (*F* = 0) when there are three phases.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] Therefore, in a single-component system, this three-phase mixture can only exist at a single temperature and pressure, which is known as a triple point.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] Here there are two equations *μ*sol(*T*, *p*) = *μ*liq(*T*, *p*) = *μ*vap(*T*, *p*), which are sufficient to determine the two variables T and p.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] In the diagram for CO2 the triple point is the point at which the solid, liquid and gas phases come together, at 5.2 bar and 217 K.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] It is also possible for other sets of phases to form a triple point, for example in the water system there is a triple point where ice I, ice III and liquid can coexist.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] If four phases of a pure substance were in equilibrium (*P* = 4), the phase rule would give *F* = −1, which is meaningless, since there cannot be −1 independent variables.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] This explains the fact that four phases of a pure substance (such as ice I, ice III, liquid water and water vapour) are not found in equilibrium at any temperature and pressure.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] In terms of chemical potentials there are now three equations, which cannot in general be satisfied by any values of the two variables *T* and *p*, although in principle they might be solved in a special case where one equation is mathematically dependent on the other two.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] In practice, however, the coexistence of more phases than allowed by the phase rule normally means that the phases are not all in true equilibrium.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] For binary mixtures of two chemically independent components, *C* = 2 so that *F* = 4 − *P*.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] In addition to temperature and pressure, the other degree of freedom is the composition of each phase, often expressed as mole fraction or mass fraction of one component.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] As an example, consider the system of two completely miscible liquids such as toluene and benzene, in equilibrium with their vapours.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] This system may be described by a boiling-point diagram which shows the composition (mole fraction) of the two phases in equilibrium as functions of temperature (at a fixed pressure).
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] Four thermodynamic variables which may describe the system include temperature (*T*), pressure (*p*), mole fraction of component 1 (toluene) in the liquid phase (*x*1L), and mole fraction of component 1 in the vapour phase (*x*1V).
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] However, since two phases are present (*P* = 2) in equilibrium, only two of these variables can be independent (*F* = 2).
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] This is because the four variables are constrained by two relations: the equality of the chemical potentials of liquid toluene and toluene vapour, and the corresponding equality for benzene.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] For given *T* and *p*, there will be two phases at equilibrium when the overall composition of the system (**system point**) lies in between the two curves.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] A horizontal line (isotherm or tie line) can be drawn through any such system point, and intersects the curve for each phase at its equilibrium composition.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] The quantity of each phase is given by the lever rule (expressed in the variable corresponding to the *x*-axis, here mole fraction).
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] For the analysis of fractional distillation, the two independent variables are instead considered to be liquid-phase composition (x1L) and pressure.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] In that case the phase rule implies that the equilibrium temperature (boiling point) and vapour-phase composition are determined.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] Liquid–vapour phase diagrams for other systems may have azeotropes (maxima or minima) in the composition curves, but the application of the phase rule is unchanged.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] The only difference is that the compositions of the two phases are equal exactly at the azeotropic composition.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] Consider an aqueous solution containing sodium chloride (NaCl), potassium chloride (KCl), sodium bromide (NaBr), and potassium bromide (KBr), in equilibrium with their respective solid phases.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] Each salt, in solid form, is a different phase, because each possesses a distinct crystal structure and composition.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] The aqueous solution itself is another phase, because it forms a homogeneous liquid phase separate from the solid salts, with its own distinct composition and physical properties.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] So, for example, if we plot the P-T phase diagram of the system, there is only one line at which all phases coexist.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] Any deviation from the line would either cause one of the salts to completely dissolve or one of the ions to completely precipitate from the solution.
[src:phase-diagrams/phase-rule] This is sometimes incorrectly called the "condensed phase rule", but it is not applicable to condensed systems subject to high pressures (for example, in geology), since the effects of these pressures are important.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] While chemically pure materials have a single melting point, chemical mixtures often partially melt at the temperature known as the **solidus** (*T*S or *T*sol), and fully melt at the higher **liquidus** temperature (*T*L or *T*liq).
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] The solidus is always less than or equal to the liquidus, but they need not coincide.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] If a gap exists between the solidus and liquidus it is called the freezing range, and within that gap, the substance consists of a mixture of solid and liquid phases (like a slurry).
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] Such is the case, for example, with the olivine (forsterite-fayalite) system, which is common in Earth's mantle.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] In chemistry, materials science, and physics, the liquidus temperature specifies the temperature above which a material is completely liquid, and the maximum temperature at which crystals can co-exist with the melt in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] The solidus is the locus of temperatures (a curve on a phase diagram) below which a given substance is completely solid (crystallized).
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] The solidus temperature specifies the temperature below which a material is completely solid, and the minimum temperature at which a melt can co-exist with crystals in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] Liquidus and solidus are mostly used for impure substances (mixtures) such as glasses, metal alloys, ceramics, rocks, and minerals.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] Lines of liquidus and solidus appear in the phase diagrams of binary solid solutions, as well as in eutectic systems away from the invariant point.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] For pure elements or compounds, e.g. pure copper, pure water, etc. the liquidus and solidus are at the same temperature, and the term melting point may be used.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] There are also some mixtures which melt at a particular temperature, known as congruent melting.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] In a eutectic system, there is particular mixing ratio where the solidus and liquidus temperatures coincide at a point known as the invariant point.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] At the invariant point, the mixture undergoes a eutectic reaction where both solids melt at the same temperature.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] There are several models used to predict liquidus and solidus curves for various systems.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] Detailed measurements of solidus and liquidus can be made using techniques such as differential scanning calorimetry and differential thermal analysis.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] For impure substances, e.g. alloys, honey, soft drink, ice cream, etc. the melting point broadens into a melting interval.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] If the temperature is within the melting interval, one may see "slurries" at equilibrium, i.e. the slurry will neither fully solidify nor melt.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] This is why new snow of high purity on mountain peaks either melts or stays solid, while dirty snow on the ground in cities tends to become slushy at certain temperatures.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] Weld melt pools containing high levels of sulfur, either from melted impurities of the base metal or from the welding electrode, typically have very broad melting intervals, which leads to increased risk of hot cracking.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] Above the liquidus temperature, the material is homogeneous and liquid at equilibrium.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] As the system is cooled below the liquidus temperature, more and more crystals will form in the melt if one waits a sufficiently long time, depending on the material.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] Alternately, homogeneous glasses can be obtained through sufficiently fast cooling, i.e., through kinetic inhibition of the crystallization process.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] The crystal phase that crystallizes first on cooling a substance to its liquidus temperature is termed *primary crystalline phase* or *primary phase*.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] The composition range within which the primary phase remains constant is known as *primary crystalline phase field*.
[src:phase-diagrams/solidus-chemistry] The liquidus temperature is important in the glass industry because crystallization can cause severe problems during the glass melting and forming processes, and it also may lead to product failure.
